1 Introduction
**************

Pending is a standalone Emacs Lisp library for marking buffer regions
whose content will arrive asynchronously.  It provides a colored
placeholder where some asynchronously computed text is going to appear,
optionally with a spinner or progress bar, and atomically replaces it
with the result when ready.

     Calling Claude  ⠋ [████████········] 47%

   Common use cases:

   • LLM streaming responses (‘gptel’, ‘agent-shell’, your own
     Claude/OpenAI client).
   • Long-running shell commands run via ‘make-process’.
   • Network fetches via ‘url-retrieve’.
   • Arbitrary callback-driven asynchronous work.

   The library aims for four properties that make asynchronous insertion
pleasant for end users:

*Visible async*
     Users see immediately _where_ the answer will land and _that_
     something is happening.  No silent wait while staring at a static
     buffer.

*Atomic resolution*
     The swap from placeholder to result is exactly one undo step.  No
     torn intermediate states, no partial-edit history pollution.

*Edit-survival*
     While the placeholder is active, its text is read-only.
     Surrounding edits adjust the placeholder's markers automatically;
     if the user deletes the region outright, the placeholder cancels
     itself rather than resolving into deleted space.

*Backend-agnostic*
     The library does not commit to any particular async pattern; it
     provides a small primitive (token + atomic swap) that integrates
     with ‘gptel’, ‘make-process’, ‘url-retrieve’, plain timers, or your
     own callback-driven pattern.

   A single global animation timer drives all active placeholders, so
spinning N concurrent regions costs only N overlay decorations per tick,
not N timers.


