5 Simple API
************

The simple positional API is the recommended starting point.  Each
function returns a token; pass that token to
‘pending-finish’/‘pending-cancel’ when ready.

 -- Function: pending-region beg-or-token &optional end str
     Two call shapes are supported.

     *Constructor:* ‘(pending-region BEG END STR)’.  Mark the region
     ‘[BEG, END]’ in the current buffer as pending an asynchronous
     change.  When ‘BEG < END’, the overlay covers existing buffer text
     and carries ‘pending-highlight’ as its ‘face’ property so the user
     can see which characters the asynchronous change will rewrite (the
     underlying buffer text is untouched -- only the overlay carries a
     face).  STR shows as a lighter badge at BEG via the overlay's
     ‘before-string’, faced with ‘pending-lighter’.  If BEG equals END,
     the overlay carries no face; only the lighter shows.  Returns a
     TOKEN (a ‘pending’ struct) usable with ‘pending-finish’,
     ‘pending-cancel’, and ‘pending-goto’.

     *Accessor:* ‘(pending-region TOKEN)’.  Back-compat accessor: return
     the live overlay object owned by TOKEN, or nil.  Equivalent to
     ‘(pending-ov TOKEN)’.

          (let ((tok (pending-region (region-beginning) (region-end)
                                     "summarising")))
            (gptel-request (buffer-substring (region-beginning) (region-end))
             :callback (lambda (text _) (pending-finish tok text))))

 -- Function: pending-insert pos str
     Mark POS as pending insertion of asynchronously-computed text.
     Shows STR as a lighter badge at POS. No region is highlighted (BEG
     = END). Returns a token.  When eventually resolved with text via
     ‘pending-finish’, the text is inserted at POS.

          (pending-insert (point) "fetching weather")

 -- Function: pending-finish token text
     Atomically replace TOKEN's region with TEXT. Transition to
     ‘:resolved’.  Returns t on success, nil if TOKEN was already in a
     terminal state.

     The replacement happens inside an ‘atomic-change-group’, so undo
     sees one step.  ‘inhibit-read-only’ and
     ‘inhibit-modification-hooks’ are bound during the swap.  Side
     effects: removes the overlay, clears markers, unregisters the
     token, cancels any deadline timer, and runs the ‘:on-resolve’
     callback once (errors there are caught and warned).

          (pending-finish tok "Hello, world!")

 -- Function: pending-cancel p &optional reason
     Cancel P, optionally with REASON (default ‘:cancelled-by-user’).
     Calls P's ‘:on-cancel’ callback _first_, so the caller can abort
     underlying work (e.g.  kill a process).  Then transitions P to
     ‘:cancelled’ and replaces the region with a small cancelled glyph
     (‘✗ REASON’).  The inserted glyph is plain text -- the library
     never adds a ‘face’ property to text it inserts itself; surrounding
     font-lock applies normally.

     The ‘:on-cancel’ callback is wrapped in ‘condition-case’; a buggy
     callback (or one that signals ‘quit’) does not break the cancel
     pipeline.

          (pending-cancel tok)               ; cancelled-by-user
          (pending-cancel tok :timed-out)    ; explicit reason

 -- Command: pending-goto token
     Move point to TOKEN's start position.  Switches to TOKEN's buffer
     if not already current.  Signals a ‘user-error’ if the buffer is
     dead.

     Interactively, prompts via ‘completing-read’ over the registered
     placeholders.

          M-x pending-goto RET <pick from list> RET

 -- Command: pending-list
     Display all registered pending placeholders in a tabulated-list
     buffer.  *Note Interactive UI::, for the full description.

 -- Function: pending-alist
     Return an alist snapshot ‘((ID . STRUCT) ...)’ of all currently
     registered pending placeholders.  Order is unspecified.  This is a
     fresh list; mutating it does not affect the registry.

          (length (pending-alist))                                 ; how many
          (mapcar (lambda (cell) (pending-label (cdr cell)))       ; all labels
                  (pending-alist))

 -- Command: pending-cancel-at-point
     Cancel the pending placeholder at point.  Signals a ‘user-error’ if
     no placeholder covers point.  Bound to ‘RET’ and ‘mouse-1’ over a
     placeholder by ‘pending-region-map’.


