9 Promise adapter
*****************

‘pending-aio.el’ is an optional add-on that turns a ‘pending’ token into
an ‘aio-promise’, so coroutine- based callers using the ‘aio’ library
can ‘aio-await’ a placeholder's resolution.  It is gated behind an
explicit ‘(require 'pending-aio)’ and depends on ‘aio’ -- the main
‘pending’ package does not pull ‘aio’ in.

 -- Function: pending-as-promise token

     Return an ‘aio-promise’ that resolves when ‘TOKEN’ reaches a
     terminal state (‘:resolved’, ‘:rejected’, ‘:cancelled’, or
     ‘:expired’).  The promise resolves with ‘TOKEN’ itself, so the
     caller can read ‘(pending-status TOKEN)’, ‘(pending-reason TOKEN)’,
     or ‘(pending-resolved-at TOKEN)’ on the awaited value to discover
     how the placeholder ended.

     If ‘TOKEN’ is already terminal at call time, the returned promise
     resolves immediately with ‘TOKEN’.

     The adapter chains itself onto ‘TOKEN’'s ‘on-resolve’ slot.  Any
     pre-existing ‘on-resolve’ callback is invoked first (with errors
     caught and reported as a ‘pending’ warning) so installing the
     adapter does not silently displace caller-supplied handlers.

          (require 'pending-aio)

          (aio-defun my-async-fn ()
            (let* ((token (pending-make (current-buffer) :label "Working"))
                   (resolved (aio-await (pending-as-promise token))))
              (message "Token %s ended with status %s"
                       (pending-id resolved)
                       (pending-status resolved))))


